Replaces the mocked `routes/alert_center.ts` (never mounted) with a
bridging view module + thin route handlers on the already-mounted
`routes/alerts.ts`. The Alert Center dashboard page now reads real
in-process state:

- `/api/alerts/summary` — counts + priority breakdown + system health
- `/api/alerts/active-feed` — CenterAlert[] (real alerts + burning SLOs)
- `/api/alerts/rules` — one rule per AlertType + one per SLO
- `/api/alerts/channels` — Dashboard / Log / Webhook / SSE with real status
- `/api/alerts/anomalies` — burn-rate metrics as monitored signal
- `/api/alerts/escalation` — 3-tier listing derived from env config
- `/api/alerts/health` — alert engine / dispatcher / router subsystem state
- `POST /api/alerts/acknowledge` + `POST /api/alerts/resolve` — body-based

New bridging module `lib/alerts/alert_center_view.ts` owns the shape
translation: internal Alert (type/severity/message/details/timestamp) →
dashboard CenterAlert (id/ruleId/ruleName/priority/category/status).

Dashboard `alert-center.tsx` now calls `/alerts/active-feed` and adapts
the CenterAlert shape to its existing row renderer via a tiny
`toRelTime` helper — mock data falls back only if the fetch fails.

